## 4. Executing the Vision: The Leipzig Cycles (1723–1727)

Bach organized his creative life into "Annual Cycles" (_Jahrgänge_), providing a new work for every Sunday and feast day—roughly sixty performances annually.

### 4.1 The Blueprint: The Lutheran Liturgical Calendar

The pace of Bach's work was dictated by the church year. Notably, Leipzig observed _tempus clausum_ (closed time) during the last three Sundays of Advent and the five Sundays of Lent, when concerted music was forbidden. Bach used these "silent" weeks to compose the massive works required for the high festivals that followed.

